2026-03-27 14:21:54,646 | INFO | USER: On March 3, 2026, the City Transit Research Office released a pilot study about late-night bus reliability in three neighborhoods: Eastgate, Riverview, and North Square. The study lasted 8 weeks and examined 1,260 total bus trips between 10:00 p.m. and 1:00 a.m.According to the report, Eastgate had the highest on-time performance at 91%, while Riverview recorded 84% and North Square recorded 79%. However, North Square showed the biggest improvement during the pilot, rising from 68% on-time performance in the first week to 79% by the end of week eight.The report states that two interventions were introduced. First, dispatchers began using a real-time traffic adjustment tool on March 10. Second, the city added one backup driver on Fridays and Saturdays starting March 17. Researchers concluded that the traffic adjustment tool likely improved timing consistency across all three neighborhoods, but they said the evidence for the backup driver was mixed because staffing records were incomplete for two weekends.Passenger complaints also changed during the pilot. Complaints about long waits dropped from 96 in the first two weeks to 51 in the final two weeks. But complaints about overcrowding increased from 18 to 29 over the same period, especially on the Riverview line.The report did not recommend expanding the program citywide yet. Instead, it recommended another 10-week trial with better staffing records and weather data, because four nights of heavy rain may have affected delays in North Square. The office estimated the total pilot cost at $48,000, not including existing driver salaries.
